etymologies: mid 19th century (in an earlier sense). From scriggle

definitions: An irregular written or printed line or mark; a squiggle.

etymologies: early 18th century. Imitative of a wriggling movement, probably modelled on struggle and wriggle

definitions: To wriggle; to struggle to move or escape. Also with adverbs, as about, away, through, etc. English regional (chiefly East Anglian) or informal in later use.
